title: For Sale:  Japanese Papa Nambu 8mm handgun & holster
postcontent: Japanese Papa Nambu 8mm pistol with original holster, one box of 8mm Nambu shells.  Gun was brought back from Okwanawa by a Navy soldier who got it off a Marine that they picked up after the battle on the island was over.  The gun is all original with Tokyo arsenal markings.  The serial number on the bottom of the magazine doesn't match the gun, which most all of them didn't anyway.  This is also known as the Model A or the Grandfather Nambu.  The Japanese officers had to purchase these with their own money.  The barrel is shiny without any dark spots or pitting, riflings are in excellent shape, wooden handle has 12 small X's on one side, we all know what that meant.  It has sort of a brown patina to it, with no pitting and would be what you would expect from a gun that has been through what it has.  The holster has the bottom clasp that snaps into the top one is missing, other than that it's in good shape.  I saw a holster just like it in worse shape sell on gunbroker for $1250.  And about 12 years ago I had a guy that collected german lugers and papa nambu's and he appraise it at $3600. even though the magazine doesnt' match the gun, he said you could take off $200.-$300. off of the hand gun but it really didn't hurt the value of the gun since most of them didn't match anyway.There were only about 8000 of these made and the serial number on this gun is in the 2000 range.  The lanyard ring swivels, on the handgrip, so it's an Army model.  This is a true piece of history for a collector.  I've never shot the gun, but when I was a very young I remember watching my dad shoot it and it worked flawlessly.  He gave it to me, I cleaned it and put it in my safe.  I get it out and oil it and wipe it off every so often.I can email more pictures if requested.Please, serious inquiries only.  Cash only.  Price is not negotiable.Local cash sale only, I won't mail it out.

Yes, that means this is one of the "safe shooters" so highly sought. It has several stock cartooches indicating one, or possibly two rearsenal stints after the war, which is where it recieved the green-gray parkarization common from late 1918 through WW2 and a new (but still WW1) bolt.
